<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="148" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,310,706,732]" box="[189,310,706,732]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,706,732]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,706,732]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[187,1400,754,927]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">
Among other members of 
<emphasis box="[487,627,754,780]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Distichalius</emphasis>
Casey, 1915, the new species can be distinguished by the following combination of characters: body relatively small, head with interocular punctures (red arrows in 
<figureCitation box="[1292,1381,790,817]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[190,233,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[197,1379,731,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-146@8.[189,1398,716,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 1. Quedius gissaricus sp. nov., holotype (ZIN). A. Habitus (interocular punctures indicated by red arrows). B–D. Aedeagus.B. From parameral side. C. Apical portion of paramere (underside). D. Median lobe (laterally). E. Sternite VIII. Scale bars: A =1 mm; B–E = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658769/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), elytra with rough and very sparse punctation arranged in irregular rows; median lobe of symmetrical aedeagus simple, without apical lobes, with distinct apex; paramere with several sensory peg setae apically arranged in short rows along parameral margins with apical setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="148" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,324,967,993]" box="[189,324,967,993]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,967,993]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,967,993]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1398,1015,1078]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">
The species name ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2022" box="[429,551,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gissaricus">
<emphasis box="[429,551,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">gissaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ (latinized adjective) is derived from the mountain range where this specimen was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
